g.ed:note: If you already use CMM for Software Process Maturity Assessment, adapt CMM  to Assess Architecture Process Maturity was well. It does make sense to use consistent Maturity Assessment methodologies.

Level 1  Initial stage; no architecture to speak of: Although decreasing, there are still a large number of ITOs that are at the SEI models initial state of architecture development. Little architecture process might be in place, besides a handful of standards for desktop systems, servers, or DBMSs. No formal architecture processes are in place, though there may be several informal processes that declare product standards. There is no unified architecture development process across technologies and LOBs. There is no explicit linkage to business issues in the technology standards that do exist. Getting out of this stage requires establishing an architecture team, tasked with developing an architecture process that is repeatable within the enterprise. Linkages to business leaders and to the IT leadership team must be established and used to drive credibility for the EA effort.

Level 2  Repeatable; an architecture process exists: Companies emerging from the chaos of Level 1 into Level 2 will have an informal process for developing the architecture components. There will be established gates through which technology acquisition choices must pass. There will be implicit linkages to business issues, mostly characterized as reducing TCO. The architecture process might not be repeated regularly, but occasionally be resurrected to address some technological deficiency. To advance to the next stage, the architecture process needs to be more completely defined and executed consistently across the enterprise. The architecture process must develop clear roles and responsibilities and include managed governance of application delivery in accordance with the architecture.

Level 3  Defined; consistent process, consistently applied: At Level 3, the process for developing the architecture is well defined and communicated and largely followed. Architecture deliverables are linked to business issues, not just technology engineering or operations issues. The EA process is executed at regular intervals to refresh the architecture content. Application delivery is linked to architecture deliverables, providing review of application projects against the architecture standards. Deviations from the architecture are fed back into the architecture development process. To move to the next stage, processes cycle times and quality parameters need to be captured and measured.

Level 4  Managed; measured process parameters: Quality metrics associated with the architecture process are captured and measured at Level 4. These metrics include the cycles times necessary to generate revisions to the architecture, stability of the technical environment, and time to market for application delivery using the componentry of the architecture (from concept through deployment to end users). Although these processes are being measured, it is the feedback from these measurements into process optimizations that moves the architecture process to Level 5, optimizing.

Level 5  Optimized; process metrics drive process improvements: Processes at the optimizing level use metrics gathered at Level 4 to drive continuous process improvements. We have identified no architecture efforts in the G2000 that could be described as Level 5.

The definition of the five maturity levels as to be adapted to the domain of Architecture Development Processes.

The assessment criteria are completely new designed to assess the current state of the architecture processes.
